Travel case study¶

Data¶

  • clicks.csv Contains the daily number of aggregated clickouts in a hypothetical market. Table schema: date_ymd, click_count. To be used in tasks 1 and 2.

  • hotel_details.csv Contains the following properties of a sample of hotels: hotel_id, city, country, stars, hotel_rating. All the hotels are in one of the following cities: Hanoi, Los Angeles, Miami, New York, Rio de Janeiro, and Stockholm. To be used in tasks 1, 3, and 4.

  • hotel_metrics.csv Contains a number of daily metrics (date_ymd, hotel_id, impression_count, click_count, booking_count, avg_cpc, avg_clicked_price, avg_length_of_stay, avg_time_to_travel) of a list of accommodations. To be used in tasks 1, 3, and 4.

The columns on these datasets are defined as described below (some columns are present in more than one dataset):

  • date_ymd: Date in the yyyymmdd format
  • click_count: Number of clickouts made by users.
  • hotel_id: Unique identifier of a given accommodation.
  • city: City where the accommodation is located.
  • country: Country where the accommodation is located.
  • stars: Number of stars of the corresponding hotel.
  • hotel_rating: Average rating given by users on the corresponding accommodation. The scale goes from 0 to 100.
  • impression_count: Number of impressions of the corresponding accommodation.
  • booking_count: Number of bookings made on the corresponding accommodation.
  • avg_cpc: The average clicked CPC of the corresponding accommodation.
  • avg_clicked_price: The average clicked price per night of the accommodation.
  • avg_length_of_stay: The average clicked length of stay.
  • avg_time_to_travel: The average clicked time to travel.

Glossary¶

  • advertiser: A booking platform. Some real-life examples of advertisers would be Expedia, Booking.com, Hotels.com, Trip.com, ...
  • clickout: These are clicks made on specific hotel deals, leading the user to the landing page of the corresponding advertiser.
  • impression: An impression is defined as the number of times the corresponding hotel appears in the result list of a given search.
  • session: A session is defined as an active usage of the travel website for a continuous amount of time. One given session is contained on a single date.
  • CPC: Cost per click. Each clickout the user performs has a CPC linked to it. The advertiser that receives the clickout pays the corresponding CPC value. The value of the CPC is defined by the advertiser in the form of a daily bid. For simplicity, you can assume that each hotel_id has a single CPC placed by each advertiser on a given day.
  • Length of stay: Number of nights between check-in and check-out date.
  • Time to travel: Number of days between the clickout and the check-in dates.

Removing (clipping) outliers

In [ ]:
def remove_outliers(feature: pd.Series, lower_perc: int=1, upper_perc: int=98) -> list:
    lower_bound, upper_bound = np.percentile(feature.values, [lower_perc, upper_perc])
    return np.clip(feature, lower_bound, upper_bound)

for col in interesting_cols:
    hotel_metrics[col] = remove_outliers(hotel_metrics[col])

def plot_clicks_with_weekdays(clicks: pd.DataFrame, period: slice) -> Figure:
    
    clicks_slice = clicks[period]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 10))

    ax.plot(clicks_slice['date_ymd'], clicks_slice['click_count'])

    ax.set_xticks(clicks_slice['date_ymd'])
    joint_label = [f'{day} ({ts.day}/{ts.month})' for (ts, day) in clicks_slice[['date_ymd', 'weekday']].values]
    ax.set_xticklabels(joint_label, rotation=80)
    ax.grid()
    ax.set_title(f'Clicks from {clicks_slice["date_ymd"].iloc[0].date()} to {clicks_slice["date_ymd"].iloc[-1].date()}')

    return fig

Finding the right model¶

At first we will split the dataset into train, val and test groups. On this data we will do the following:

  1. Find transformation to lower the variance of data
  2. Fit models to train, find best parameters for (seasonal) ARIMA
  3. Make daily predictions on val, add new data to models after each prediction
  4. Make predictions for the remaining data, evaluate on gapped test
  5. Choose best model, update it with all available data and make predictions for September

def forecast_one_step(model: ARIMA, alpha: float=0.05) -> tuple:
    '''
    Function from "Stock market prediction" example
    https://alkaline-ml.com/pmdarima/usecases/stocks.html#pre-modeling-analysis
    '''
    fc, conf_int = model.predict(n_periods=1, return_conf_int=True, alpha=alpha)
    return fc.tolist()[0], np.asarray(conf_int).tolist()[0]

def plot_arima_models(
    data: pd.Series,
    models: List[ARIMA],
    metrics: Dict['str', callable],
    update_model: bool= False,
    conf_alpha: float = 0.05,
    gap: int = 0,
    figsize:tuple=(12, 18),
) -> Figure:
    
    if gap and update_model:
        print('Due to using gap, model should not be updated with new data')
        update_model = False
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(models), 1, figsize=figsize)
    
    fig.suptitle('Data vs model predictions', fontsize=16)
    
    for i, model in enumerate(models):
        if update_model:
            model_fc = []
            model_ci = []
            for obs in data:
                fc, ci = forecast_one_step(model, alpha=conf_alpha)
                model_fc.append(fc)
                model_ci.append(ci)
                model.update(obs)
            
            model_ci = np.array(model_ci)
        else:
            model_fc, model_ci = model.predict(n_periods=len(data) + gap, return_conf_int=True, alpha=conf_alpha)
        
        model_fc = model_fc[gap:]
        model_ci = model_ci[gap:]
                
        axes[i].scatter(data.index, data, marker='x', label='real data')
        axes[i].set_xticks(data.index.tolist())
        axes[i].set_xticklabels([ts.date() for ts in data.index], rotation=15)

        metric_values = []
        for metric_name, metric in metrics.items():
            metric_values.append(f'{metric_name}={metric(data, model_fc):.4f}')

        color = next(COLORS)
        
        axes[i].plot(
            data.index,
            model_fc,
            label=f'preds ({", ".join(metric_values)})',
            color=color,
        )
        axes[i].fill_between(
            data.index,
            model_ci[:, 0],
            model_ci[:, 1],
            alpha=0.1,
            label=f'{(1-conf_alpha)*100:.2f}% CI',
            color=color
        )

        axes[i].set_title(f'{str(model)}')
        axes[i].legend()
        axes[i].grid()
    
    fig.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])
    
    return fig

)

The performance is quite close within models with explicit seasonality.

For the version without seasonal features, we can see that the best p term is quite high, so as the model complexity. And the SMAPE is still worse.

Now I want to further analyze the candidates for the best predictive model. Basically, I want to check if the residuals are autocorrelated, and are they normally distributed

In [ ]:
for model in models:
    model.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(10, 8), lags=30)
    plt.suptitle(f'{str(model)} diagnostics')
    plt.grid()

plt.show()

Well, to be honest no model is perfect :)

Some observations:

  • The model without seasonality is the worst here. Its correlogram suggests many unexplained dependencies and the residuals are more distant from Normal distribution than in other models;
  • On ACF plots we see that there are some potentially unexplained patterns, as some significant autocorrelations are found;
  • On the bottom left graphs we see deviations of residuals distributions from the red line in all of our models. But these deviations are smaller for seasonal ones;
  • Residuals on seasonal models oscillate around zero, which is good. But there might be a small bias in predictions;
  • Seems like the $4^{th}$ model, ARIMA (0, 1, 1)(2, 0, 2)[21] might be the best model here

The deviations can be explained with the high values in clicks specific to July. If given more data, we might construct a better model.

Put it into a function

In [ ]:
def generate_features(
    hotel_metrics: pd.DataFrame,
    hotel_details: pd.DataFrame,
    feature_agg_columns: list
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    
    united_hotel_metrics = pd.merge(hotel_metrics, hotel_details, how='left', on='hotel_id')
    united_hotel_metrics.drop(columns=['date_ymd', 'country'], inplace=True)
        
    data_agg_metrics = united_hotel_metrics[united_hotel_metrics['city'] != 'unknown'][feature_agg_columns].mean().to_frame()
    city_agg_metrics = united_hotel_metrics[united_hotel_metrics['city'] != 'unknown'].groupby(by=['city'], as_index=False)[feature_agg_columns].mean()
    
    cities = city_agg_metrics['city'].values

    for feature in feature_agg_columns:
        united_hotel_metrics[f'{feature}_all_ratio'] = united_hotel_metrics[feature] / data_agg_metrics.loc[feature].values[0]
        for city in cities:
            united_hotel_metrics[f'{feature}_{city.split()[0].lower()}_ratio'] = united_hotel_metrics[feature] / city_agg_metrics.loc[city_agg_metrics['city'] == city][feature].values[0]
    
    return united_hotel_metrics

Initial models estimate¶

We will estimate model performances on train features set using k-fold cross-validation. At first, we will guess the parameters and later search for the most optimal ones.

As we have a class disbalance here, we must include some kind of weighting to our metrics. Otherwise scores like accuracy will not be much informative. Indeed, we will have about 50% accuracy just by predicting the major class, if we do not do any adjustments

In [ ]:
def get_name(clf) -> str:
    if isinstance(clf, type):
        return clf.__name__
    return clf.__class__.__name__

def cross_validate_kfold(
    clf: 'classifier',
    X: np.array,
    y: np.array,
    score_funcs: Dict[str, callable],
    cv: int = 5,
    shuffle: bool = True,
    random_seed: int = RANDOM_SEED,
) -> dict:
    '''
    Do cross-validation for the classifier and return scores
    '''
    
    clf_scores = defaultdict(list)
    kfolds = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=cv, shuffle=shuffle, random_state=random_seed)
    
    for fold_count, (train_part, val_part) in enumerate(kfolds.split(X, y)):
        train_x, train_labels = X[train_part], y[train_part]
        val_x, val_labels = X[val_part], y[val_part]

        clf.fit(train_x, train_labels)        
        val_preds = clf.predict(val_x)

        for score_name, func in score_funcs.items():
            score = func(val_labels, val_preds)
            clf_scores[score_name].append(score)
    
    return clf_scores

def test_classifier(
    clf: 'classifier',
    X: np.array,
    y: np.array,
    score_funcs: Dict[str, callable]=None,
    cv:int = 5,
    shuffle: bool = True,
    random_seed: int = RANDOM_SEED,
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    '''
    Return a DataFrame of estimates of classifier performance on cross-validation
    '''
    
    res = pd.DataFrame()
    clf_name = get_name(clf)
    
    res['model'] = [clf_name]
    
    res.set_index('model')
        
    clf_scores = cross_validate_kfold(clf, X, y, score_funcs, cv, shuffle, random_seed)
    
    for score_name, score_values in clf_scores.items():
        res[score_name] = [np.mean(score_values)]
        
    return res

Define scoring functions we will look at.

Given the class imbalance we want to pay attention both to recall and precicion, thus the weighted F1-score might be a good candidate for the metric. We will also look at macro averaging just as an unweighted reference.

(Reminder. Macro will compute metric for each class and then take the average. It does not care about classes disbalance. Micro will aggregate the contributions of all classes. In multi-class task like ours micro-f1 would be essentially the accuracy)

In [ ]:
score_functions = {
    'f1_macro': partial(f1_score, average='macro'),
    'f1_weighted': partial(f1_score, average='weighted'),
    'accuracy': accuracy_score,
    'accuracy_weighted': balanced_accuracy_score
}

Model analysis¶

Confusion Matrices¶

It is useful to understand the performance of the model on different classes. Especially interesting is how it handles the minor class (Hanoi) and how it differentiates cities in USA from other classes and between each other.

In [ ]:
from typing import Optional, Iterable

def plot_confusion_matrices(
    models: list, 
    X_test: np.ndarray,
    y_test: np.ndarray,
    class_labels: Optional[Iterable[str]] = None,
    figsize: tuple = (12, 12),
) -> Figure:
  
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(models), 1, figsize=figsize)
    fig.suptitle('Confusion matrices for classifiers', fontsize=16)
    
    for i, model in enumerate(models):
        ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_estimator(model, X_test, y_test, display_labels=class_labels, ax=axes[i], xticks_rotation=30)
        axes[i].set_title(f'{get_name(model)}')
        
    fig.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])

    return fig

def show_feature_importances(clf, columns):
    imps = np.array(clf.feature_importances_)
    sorted_features = [(x, col) for (x, col) in sorted(zip(imps, columns), key=lambda pair: pair[0])]
    return dict(sorted_features[::-1])

Based on models' estimates of features importances and shap scores, we could be able to lower the feature space. For example, it seems like features connected with booking count and clicks count are almost useless. By iteratively refitting the model to a subset of the best features we might achieve the same or better (if unimportant features only add noise) quality using less data and save on storage.

(Optional) Organize preprocessing into functions¶

early draft for organizing preprocessing in a python file

In [ ]:
%%writefile preprocess.py

from typing import Optional

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import scale


METRICS_COLS = ['impression_count', 'click_count', 'booking_count', 'avg_cpc', 'avg_clicked_price', 'avg_length_of_stay', 'avg_time_to_travel']
FEATURES_COLS = METRICS_COLS + ['stars', 'hotel_rating']

def clip_outliers(feature: pd.Series, lower_perc: int=1, upper_perc: int=98) -> np.ndarray:
    lower_bound, upper_bound = np.percentile(feature.values, [lower_perc, upper_perc])
    return np.clip(feature, lower_bound, upper_bound)

def fill_missing_rating(hotel_details: pd.DataFrame, stars2rating: Optional[dict] = None, special_char: str = '\\N') -> pd.DataFrame:
    if stars2rating is None:
        stars_ratings = hotel_details[hotel_details['hotel_rating'] >= 0].groupby(by=['stars'], as_index=False)['hotel_rating'].mean().to_frame()
        stars2rating = stars_ratings['mean'].to_dict()

    df_corrected = hotel_details.replace(special_char, -10)
    df_corrected['hotel_rating'] = df_corrected['hotel_rating'].astype('float')
    df_corrected.loc[df_corrected['hotel_rating'] < 0, ['hotel_rating']] = df_corrected[df_corrected['hotel_rating'] < 0]['stars'].apply(lambda star: stars2rating[star])
    
    return df_corrected

def create_features_df(
    hotel_metrics: pd.DataFrame,
    hotel_details: pd.DataFrame,
    feature_agg_columns: list,
    data_agg_metrics: Optional[pd.DataFrame] = None,
    city_agg_metrics: Optional[pd.DataFrame] = None,
    missing_city_kw: str = 'unknown',
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    
    united_hotel_metrics = pd.merge(hotel_metrics, hotel_details, how='left', on='hotel_id')
    united_hotel_metrics.drop(columns=['date_ymd', 'country'], inplace=True)
    
    if data_agg_metrics is None:
        data_agg_metrics = united_hotel_metrics[united_hotel_metrics['city'] != missing_city_kw][feature_agg_columns].mean().to_frame()
    
    if city_agg_metrics is None:
        city_agg_metrics = united_hotel_metrics[united_hotel_metrics['city'] != missing_city_kw].groupby(by=['city'], as_index=False)[feature_agg_columns].mean()
    
    cities = city_agg_metrics['city'].values

    for feature in feature_agg_columns:
        united_hotel_metrics[f'{feature}_all_ratio'] = united_hotel_metrics[feature] / data_agg_metrics.loc[feature].values[0]
        for city in cities:
            united_hotel_metrics[f'{feature}_{city.split()[0].lower()}_ratio'] = united_hotel_metrics[feature] / city_agg_metrics.loc[city_agg_metrics['city'] == city][feature].values[0]
    
    united_hotel_metrics.drop(columns=['hotel_id', 'city'], inplace=True)
    return united_hotel_metrics

def run_preprocess_pipeline(
    hotel_metrics: pd.DataFrame,
    hotel_details: pd.DataFrame,
    data_agg_metrics: Optional[pd.DataFrame] = None,
    city_agg_metrics: Optional[pd.DataFrame] = None,
    stars2missing_rating: Optional[dict] = None
) -> np.array:
    
    for col in METRICS_COLS:
        hotel_metrics[col] = clip_outliers(hotel_metrics[col])

    hotel_details = fill_missing_rating(hotel_details, stars2missing_rating)

    new_features = create_features_df(hotel_metrics, hotel_details, FEATURES_COLS, data_agg_metrics, city_agg_metrics)
    
    return scale(new_features)

def run_preprocess_pipeline_with_paths(
    hotel_metrics_path: str,
    hotel_details_path: str,
    data_agg_metrics_path: Optional[str] = None,
    city_agg_metrics_path: Optional[str] = None,
    stars2rating_path: Optional[str] = None
) -> np.array:
    '''
    Return features for CatBoost model inference given hotel metrics and pre-calculated statistics.
    If the paths to statistics are not provided, they will be recalculated on provided hotel data.
    '''
    
    hotel_details = pd.read_csv(hotel_details_path)
    hotel_metrics = pd.read_csv(hotel_metrics_path, parse_dates=['date_ymd'])
    
    reloaded_city_agg = pd.read_csv(city_agg_metrics_path)
    reloaded_data_agg = pd.read_csv(data_agg_metrics_path, index_col='metric')

    reloaded_stars_ratings = pd.read_csv(stars2rating_path, index_col='stars')
    stars2missing_rating = reloaded_stars_ratings['mean'].to_dict()

    return run_preprocess_pipeline(hotel_metrics, hotel_details, reloaded_data_agg, reloaded_city_agg, stars2missing_rating)

Python Workflow¶

Now that you have the model from Task 3, let’s imagine the situation where the model was accepted and we want to put it into production. For that, we need to build a Python/PySpark workflow.

I guess, general pipeline should be the following.

Initial steps, after we decided to keep the model and prepare it to run in production:

  1. Research, train different models on a large train set, find the best and fine-tune parameters;
  2. Create stable test dataset. It will be used for evalution of future changes to our model;
  3. Save best candidate's model parameters to some storage. It might be a simple solution like having a folder with model weights named in a way model_[creationDate]. Or we could use something like MLFlow to organize better. Or smth in the middle like noSQL database with dictionary files (e.g. Mongo);
  4. Save data needed for preprocessing. In my case I should save statistics that I use for features generations. It might be a good idea to revisit them from time to time and create newer versions of the model (if it outperforms the initial one on the test set, of course).

More implementation-specific steps:

  1. The main script should:

    • start on schedule (like on cron) or when called,
    • load the new data from the upward stream (e.g. read from a database),
    • load the model with best tuned parameters,
    • call preprocessor for the new data, generate necessary features as were in the training procedure,
    • make prediction,
    • write data to the same stream (e.g. write to SQL database)

  2. There sould be some mechanic to enable automatic model retraining. For example, once in a few weeks, we run the pipeline with the only change in train data (newer). It might help to better adapt the model to current circumstances.
